-- Italy Stocks Gain; Azimut, DiaSorin, Fiat, Intesa, Prysmian, Sogefi Move
-- Francesca Cinelli
-- 2010-07-22T15:57:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-22/fiat-monte-dei-paschi-di-siena-prysmian-may-move-italy-equity-preview.html

          
          
             Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB  Index
advanced for a second day, rising 556.34, or 2.8 percent, to
20,694.26 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Milan.  
 The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  
 Azimut Holding SpA  (AZM IM), Italy’s largest independent
fund manager, increased 28 cents, or 4.2 percent, to 6.98 euros
as the Stoxx Europe 600 Index rose for a third day after reports
showed unexpected growth in Europe’s manufacturing and U.K.
retail sales.  
 Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA  (BMPS IM) rose 4 euro
cents, or 4.3 percent, to 97.7 cents, ending its six-day losing
streak. The Italian banking association ABI said in its
financial outlook report in Rome today that it expects Italian
banks’ net income to rise 1.5 percent in 2010.  
 DiaSorin SpA  (DIA IM), the supplier of diagnostics tests,
lost for the first day in three, falling 97 cents, or 3.3
percent, to 28.62 euros. BioMerieux SA cut its full-year sales
growth target to 6 percent from a previous forecast of around 7
percent. The company confirmed its full-year operating margin
target in a statement on Business Wire.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM) rose 20.5 cents, or 2.1 percent, to 9.87
euros, extending gains of 6.7 percent yesterday. UniCredit
Research SpA, Societe Generale SA and Centrobanca upgraded the
stock to “buy,” while Commerzbank AG lifted its recommendation
to “hold.” Nomura Holdings Inc. lifted its price estimate to
11 euros from 10.50 euros and kept a “neutral” rating.  
 Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) rose for a second day, gaining
15.5 cents, or 3.5 percent, to 4.65 euros. Italy’s five biggest
banks have passed the stress tests being conducted on the
European banking system, Il Messaggero reported, without citing
anyone.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) gained for the first time
in seven days, rising 11 cents, or 4.8 percent, to 2.43 euros.
 UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM) surged 6.2 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 2.05
euros.  
 Mediaset SpA  (MS IM) advanced the most in two weeks, rising
14.25 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 4.79 euros. Goldman Sachs Group
Inc. upgraded the broadcaster to “neutral” from “sell,”
citing the stock’s underperformance.  
 Piquadro SpA  (PQ IM), a leather-goods company, increased
for a second day this week, rising 4 cents, or 2.9 percent, to
1.41 euros. The fiscal year ended March 31 confirmed the
“profitability trend,” Chief Executive Officer Marco Palmieri
said in a statement distributed by the Italian exchange.  
 Prysmian SpA  (PRY IM) gained the most in almost two months,
rising 56 cents, or 4.5 percent, to 13.11 euros. The second
quarter was better than the first, Chief Executive Officer
Valerio Battista told Il Sole 24 Ore in an interview. The
world’s second-biggest cable maker now sees signs of recovery,
Battista said.  
 Tod’s SpA  (TOD IM) advanced 3.55 euros, or 6.4 percent, to
59.15 euros, the highest since October 2007. The board proposed
to use reserves for an extraordinary dividend, the Italian
luxury-goods maker known for its rubber-studded driving shoes
said today in a statement distributed by the Italian exchange.  
